      "solution": "n = int(input())\n\nSUFFIXES = [\"\", \"K\", \"M\", \"B\", \"T\"]\nmagnitude = 0\n\nwhile round(n, 1) >= 1000:\n    n /= 1000\n    magnitude += 1\n\nrounded_n = round(n, 1)\nprint(str(rounded_n if rounded_n %1 != 0 else int(rounded_n)) + SUFFIXES[magnitude])\n",
      "statement": "<<Number Abbreviation:>>\n\n<<Given a positive integer [[n]] as input:>>\n<<The goal>> is to abbreviate the [[n]] by representing it in a shorter format with a letter suffix to denote its magnitude (This abbreviation makes it easier to read the number).\n<<For example:>> input: {{56324867}} / output: {{56.3M}}\n\n<<The abbreviation should follow the convention of using letters such as:>>\n• {{K}} for thousands.\n• {{M}} for millions.\n• {{B}} for billions.\n• {{T}} for trillions.\n• If [[n]] is less than {{1000}}, then don't apply any change.\n\n<<In case [[n]] has been abbreviated ([[n]] ≥ 1000), the output should be like this:>>\n• If the abbreviated number has a decimal part other than zero: <<round it>> to the nearest tenth.\n• If the abbreviated number is a whole number, <<remove the decimal and trailing zero>>.\n• Append the appropriate letter suffix {{K}}, {{M}}, {{B}}, or {{T}} to the abbreviation.\nEg. {{564.2B}}, {{23.6T}}, {{76M}} ...\n\n<<Tip:>>\nBegin by writing the fundamental parts of the program. As you go through the different test cases, you can fix any errors that occur in specific edge cases.",
